definition.val: Studies of the gene product in development and morphogenesis, including all multicellular stages.
The interactions between a host and a pathogen, often resulting in disease; usually, Dictyostelium is used as an experimental host to study such interactions.
Materials, analyses and nomenclature used to describe the gene or its gene product.
References which report algorithmic or statistical models to investigate certain aspects of cellular processes or behaviour, but which do not perform classical experimental work.

The process of any breakdown of cellular material and / or morphogenetic changes, through processes such as apoptosis, or autophagy, which may lead to cell death; includes developmental cell death (stalk).
Expression of the gene product in the multicellular organism as determined by gene-fusion or in situ hybridization experiments.
Role and effect of the gene product on growth rates; includes studies of the gene product during growth as a life cycle phase.
References reporting studies on or with transposons or retrotransposons, their functions and processing.
Role of the gene product in its ability to form spores and spore viability studies.
Role of the gene product in the sexual cycle, including mating types and meiosis.
Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell or the multicellular organism as a result of an external stimulus.

How the expression of the gene is controlled at the level of transcription, for example, what RNA polymerase is used, what transcription factors are needed, what other factors (such as metabolic conditions) affect transcription.
The regulation of the gene product regulation by another protein, metabolic conditions, chemical inhibitors, or other factors; also includes auto-regulatory functions.
Interactions between loci identified by genetic means, including suppression, complementation, synthetic lethality, etc.
Information describing the status, actions and processes involving proteins.
The post-translational protein level in a cell or compartment (as measured by e.g. Western blot).
The role that the gene or gene product plays in regulating the activity of other genes or proteins such as by acting as a transcription factor or regulatory kinase.
References where literature topics have been added to all attached genes.
Information describing the processes involved in cell biology and genetics of Dictyostelium.
Role of the gene product in cell-substrate or cell-cell adhesion.
Where in the cell the protein or gene is located; information on the regulation and transport of the gene/protein in its compartmentalization is listed under this topic.
Evidence for the protein being part of or having an effect on the cytoskeleton.
Involvement of the gene product in cell movement in general, and in response to a chemical attractant.
Role of the gene product in the process of transporting substances into, out of, or within the cell, including pinocytosis, 'macro-pinocytosis', phagocytosis, exocytosis and intracellular transport.
Role the protein or RNA plays,  i.e. what type of enzyme the protein is, or if it functions as part of a large complex or a multi-subunit enzyme.
Mutations of the gene, including substitutions, replacements, gene fusions or deletions, and resulting in phenotypes.
Description of the gene product being part of intra - or inter-cell signaling events.
Any cellular metabolic process involving deoxyribonucleic acid. E.g. DNA  modification, replication, fidelity, repair, telomer maintenance.
Levels of RNA in the cell (expression) and any cellular metabolic process involving  ribonucleic acid. E.g.  RNA stability, structure, replication, modification, repair, splicing.
Physical or genetic mapping results.
Overall sequence features for DNA  (promoters, exons, introns, etc.) and RNA  (splice sites, poly-A sites, etc.).
Features of the hypothetical or real primary amino acid sequence of the gene product (functional domains, hydrophilic analysis, ion-binding sites, active sites, homology regions, etc).
Physical interactions that have been demonstrated between proteins by methods such as two-hybrid analysis, cross-linking studies, co-immunoprecipitations, etc.
Different names that are used for the gene or its gene product.
The known structure of the gene product, including known structural location of specific residues; includes predictions of protein structure.
New antibodies have been created and published in this paper.

References dealing with systematic analysis of large numbers of genes, e.g. micro array  and mass spec studies, comparing expression of all the genes in a genome in two different conditions, but not systematic sequencing papers.
Novel techniques used in studying the gene as well as any reagents other than constructs that might help in experimentation, including antibodies, chemical inhibitors, and purified protein.
Literature review that refers to the gene.
The molecular weight or amino acid composition of the real or hypothetical protein product.
The role of the gene product in complex social behavior, including cooperation, self- and kin recognition, altruism, and cheating.
Predictions of functions based on comparative studies using such measures as orthology.
How the protein is modified following translation, including regulatory and non-regulatory modifications, such as phosphorylation, attachment of sugars, etc.
Root of literature topic.
Cell cycle-related changes in the expression or activity of the gene product.
Refers to the control of the levels of protein (synthesized from its mRNA), where the mechanism is unknown.
Sequence and/or functional homologs of non-mammalian genes.
Homology between the Dictyostelium gene and a gene that is disease-related or involvement of a gene in a disease model.
Any association of  DNA or RNA molecules and genes with proteins; this includes association via other binding partners or  direct binding as well as information on binding sites.
Phototaxis or thermotaxis, usually in the slug, has been investigated in this study.
Information describing all processes involved during the Dictyostelium life cycle.
The substrates or ligands of the protein, including cofactors that regulate the protein's activity.
Sequence and/or functional homologs of mammalian genes.
Information describing the status, actions and processes involving nucleic acids.
Mutant strains and constructs created for experimentation on the gene of interest.
Items that appeared important to the curator but did not fit underneath a standard topic.
Phylogenetic analysis has been performed for this gene in this study.
Describes the gene product's involvement in cytokinesis or karyokinesis.

basicPropertyValues.val: A structured controlled vocabulary of literature of the slime-mold Dictyostelium discoideum.
